Mongolian Prime Minister Mendsaikhan Enkhsaikhan left here today for a five-day working visit to Japan.
During his visit, Enkhsaikhan will hold talks with his Japanese counterpart Ryutaro Hashimoto on establishing a relationship of overall partnership between the two counties to face the 21st century.
They will also sign an agreement on Japan's free economic aid to Mongolia to help stabilize its economy and promote its food production.
Mongolia and Japan established diplomatic relations in 1972.
Ever since, to develop positive relations with Japan has been one of the top priorities in Mongolia's foreign policy, with economic cooperation having a major role.
The largest donor country of Mongolia, Japan accounts for one third of its foreign aid.
In the past years, trade volume between them was on the increase, hitting 112 milliion U.S. dollars in 1996.